# From Feedback to Action: How I Built an AI-Powered Escalation Engine for Banking Ops

## The Business Problem

In commercial banking, client feedback is a leading indicator — of compliance risk, of operational friction, of churn. But most teams still triage it manually: someone reads a complaint, decides what it means, decides who should own it, and hopes it moves fast enough before the client gives up.

Two things go wrong at scale:
- **Compliance-critical issues (AML/KYC) sit in the same queue as routine service requests**, with no automatic differentiation
- **By the time an issue is routed to the right team, the window to act before client drop-off has often already narrowed**

The business question wasn't "can we build a chatbot" — it was: **can client feedback classify itself, escalate itself, and report its own status, fast enough that ops teams act before the client walks?**

## The Outcome

A working system where:
- Every piece of feedback is automatically classified and prioritized within seconds of arrival
- Compliance and infrastructure issues are routed to the right team automatically, with SLA urgency attached — before a human ever has to triage
- An ops manager can ask "how many P1 cases are open right now" in plain English and get a real, current answer — not a stale report someone pulled last week

On a 100-case synthetic dataset, the pipeline classified **19 AML-Compliance (P1), 30 Tech-Infrastructure (P2), and 51 General Service (P3) cases — 49 of which triggered an automatic escalation digest.** Every number reconciles exactly across every stage of the workflow; none of it is estimated or approximate.

This isn't a feature. It's a **shift from reactive triage to proactive, self-reporting operations** — the kind of capability that directly reduces client churn and compliance exposure, which is the actual business case, not the automation itself.

---

## How It Works (Core Functionality First)

1. **Classify** — incoming client feedback is read and categorized: AML-Compliance, Tech-Infrastructure, or General Service
2. **Check** — each category maps to a business-defined priority (AML → P1, Tech → P2, General → P3), validated against SLA time thresholds
3. **Recommend** — P1/P2 cases trigger an automatic, formatted alert to the responsible team with a clear recommended action; everything is logged to one live source of truth
4. **Ask** — an ops manager can query that live data conversationally, anytime, without opening a spreadsheet

That loop — classify, check, recommend, ask — is the ACR Framework. Everything else described below is implementation detail in service of that loop.

