## The Stack, Briefly

| Layer | Tool | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Classification & orchestration | **n8n** | Visual, auditable branching logic — every decision (category, priority, SLA status) is traceable |
| Source of truth | **Google Sheets** | Lightweight, zero infrastructure cost for a proof of concept |
| Alerting | **Gmail (via n8n)** | SLA-aware digest, no CRM/Outlook dependency required |
| Live conversational query | **Dify**, calling an **n8n webhook** as a tool | Natural-language access to always-current data |

**Why a webhook, not a static upload to Dify:** early on, I loaded classified data into Dify's knowledge base and let it answer questions via semantic search. It failed at the one thing that mattered most — counting. Semantic retrieval finds *relevant* text, it doesn't *count* rows. For a system whose whole value is trustworthy numbers, that's disqualifying. The fix: n8n exposes a live webhook that computes exact counts on demand, and Dify calls it fresh every time a question is asked. No stale data, no approximation.

**Why Dify at all, if n8n could compute everything:** n8n orchestrates; it doesn't converse. It has no native multi-turn memory, no natural-language reasoning over follow-up questions, no reformatting raw data into something a person reads comfortably. Rather than building a chat layer from scratch inside a workflow tool, Dify does that one job well — while staying cleanly decoupled from the business logic itself, which continues to live entirely in n8n. **Orchestration and conversation are different problems; this uses the right tool for each, rather than forcing one tool to do both.**

