## What Worked

- **A single, deterministic priority rule beat AI judgment.** Priority isn't asked of the model at all — it's derived from category by a fixed rule in code, after an early version showed an AI-derived priority field could quietly disagree with its own category even under schema constraints. Removing the model from that decision removed the bug class entirely.
- **SLA-awareness turned classification into urgency.** Cases aren't just labeled — they're flagged against real time thresholds, which is what actually drives ops behavior, not the label itself.
- **Separating "who computes" from "who converses"** made both halves simpler and easier to change independently.

## What I'd Flag as Risks / Lessons for Anyone Building This

- **AI-derived fields can silently disagree with each other**, even under schema constraints — validate downstream, don't assume consistency across correlated outputs
- **Iterative testing on a live append-only sheet caused real data duplication** (100 rows became 105, then 520, across repeated test runs) — a production build needs an upsert/dedup strategy (matched on a unique ID) from day one, not as an afterthought
- **Cross-platform tool integration needs explicit, matching contracts** (method, schema) on both sides — a working URL isn't the same as a working integration
- **LLMs paraphrase strict enum values even when instructed not to** — a schema expecting an exact string will occasionally get a shortened, close-but-wrong version back; normalize downstream rather than relying on exact model wording

None of these are reasons not to build this pattern — they're the standard cost of building anything real, and worth planning for upfront rather than discovering mid-build.

